=== Early Church ===
The [[Apostolic_Fathers|Apostolic Fathers]] make very little reference to wine,<ref>Raymond, p. 88.</ref> but the earliest references from the [[Church_Fathers|Church Fathers]] make it clear that the [[early_Christianity|early church]] used wine in their celebration of the Eucharist, often mixing it with water according to the prevailing custom.<ref>[[Justin_Martyr|Justin Martyr]], ''[[First_Apology|First Apology]]'', [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf01.viii.ii.lxv.html "Chapter LXV. Administration of the sacraments"] and [http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf01.viii.ii.lxvii.html "Chapter LXVII. Weekly worship of the Christians"].</ref><ref>[[Hippolytus_of_Rome|Hippolytus of Rome]] (died 235) says, "By thanksgiving the bishop shall make the bread into an image of the body of Christ, and the cup of wine mingled with water according to the likeness of the blood." Quoted in {{cite journal|author=Keith Mathison | title=Protestant Transubstantiation - Part 2: Historical Testimony | url=http://thirdmill.org/newfiles/kei_mathison/TH.Mathison.Prot.Transub.2.html | journal=IIIM Magazine Online | volume=3| issue=1 |date=January 1 to January 7, 2001 | accessdate=2007-01-22}}</ref> The [[Didache|Didache]], an early Christian treatise which is generally accepted to be from the late 1st century, instructs Christians to give a portion of their wine in support of a true [[prophet|prophet]] or, if they have no prophet resident with them, to the poor.<ref>{{cite web|title=Didache, chapter 13|url=http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/text/didache-hoole.html#13|accessdate=2007-03-16|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070528025425/http://www.earlychristianwritings.com/text/didache-hoole.html#13|archivedate=2007-05-28|deadurl=yes}}</ref>

[[Clement_of_Alexandria|Clement of Alexandria]] (died c. 215) wrote in a chapter about drinking that he admires those who adopt an austere life and "flee as far as possible from wine, shunning it as they would the danger of fire", and he suggests the young abstain from wine so as not to inflame their "wild impulses." He says Christ did not teach affected by it. "...the soul itself is wisest and best when dry." But he says taking a little [[wine_as_medicine|wine as medicine]] or for pleasure after the day's work is acceptable for those who are "moored by reason and time" such that they aren't tempted by drunkenness, and nevertheless he encourages mixing "as much water as possible" in with the wine to inhibit inebriation. He also says wine is an appropriate symbol of Jesus' blood.<ref>{{cite web |author=[[Clement_of_Alexandria|Clement of Alexandria]] |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf02.vi.iii.ii.ii.html |title=On Drinking |work=The Instructor, book 2, chapter 2 |accessdate=2007-03-15}}</ref><ref>Compare the summary in Raymond, pp. 97-104.</ref>

[[Cyprian|Cyprian]] (died 258) rejected undiluted wine in the Eucharist. He explained the meaning: water, being the people of Christ, was mingled with the blood of Christ. Also, it would be better to prevent them who drank it from getting drunk. (But Cyprian suspected some of the people who used water on its own in the Eucharist did so from a [[Gnosticism|disbelief]] in the expressed blood of Christ.)<ref>{{cite web |author=[[Cyprian|Cyprian]] |title="Epistle LXII: To Caecilius, on the Sacrament of the Cup of the Lord", §11 |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf05.i.html |accessdate=2007-03-15}}</ref>

[[Methodius_of_Olympus|Methodius]] (died 312) said: "For we perceive from the Scriptures two kinds of vines which were separate from each other, and were unlike...

# The sober and joy-producing vine...
# the poison of dragons ... it is ordered that a virgin shall not taste of this vine, so that she may be sober and watchful...<ref>{{cite web |author=Methodius |title="Banquet of the Ten Virgins", Ch. 5 |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/anf05.i.html |accessdate=2013-09-13}}</ref>

[[Basil_the_Great|Basil the Great]] (died 379) likewise repudiated the views of some [[dualism|dualistic]] [[heresy|heretics]] who abhorred marriage, rejected wine, and called God's creation "polluted"<ref>{{cite book |author=[[Basil_the_Great|Basil the Great]]| chapter=Letter CXCIX: To Amphilochius, concerning the Canons |title=Basil: Letters and Select Works |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf208.html |others=Philip Schaff (ed.) |year=1895 |chapterurl=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf208.ix.cc.html |accessdate=2008-04-16}}</ref> and who substituted water for wine in the Eucharist.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Craig D. Allert |title=The State of the New Testament Canon in the Second Century: Putting Tatian's Diatessaron in Perspective |journal=Bulletin for Biblical Research |issue=9 |year=1999 |page=5 |accessdate=2008-04-16 |url=http://www.earlychurch.org.uk/pdf/bbr/tatian_allert.pdf |quote=Also among the beliefs of the [heretical] Encratites is the rejection of the drinking of wine. In fact, the Encratites even went so far as to substitute water for wine in the Eucharist service. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081011113559/http://www.earlychurch.org.uk/pdf/bbr/tatian_allert.pdf |archive-date=2008-10-11 |dead-url=yes }}</ref>

[[John_Chrysostom|John Chrysostom]] (died 407) in a homily on [http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1Ti5:23 1 Timothy 5:23] stresses moderation and adds that the biblical passage in question is useful for refuting heretics and immature Christians who say there should be no wine. He emphasizes the goodness of God's creation and adjures: "Let there be no drunkenness; for wine is the work of God, but drunkenness is the work of the devil. Wine makes not drunkenness; but intemperance produces it. Do not accuse that which is the workmanship of God, but accuse the madness of a fellow mortal."<ref>{{cite web |author=[[John_Chrysostom|John Chrysostom]] |title=First Homily on the Statues |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf109.xix.iii.html |accessdate=2008-06-08 |pages=paras 11f}}</ref>

The virtue of temperance passed from Greek philosophy into Christian ethics and became one of the four [[cardinal_virtues|cardinal virtues]] under [[Ambrose|St. Ambrose]]<ref>{{cite web |author=[[Ambrose|Ambrose]] |title=Book I, chapter XLIII |work=On the Duties of the Clergy |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf210.iv.i.ii.xliii.html |accessdate=2007-03-15}}</ref> and [[Augustine_of_Hippo|St. Augustine]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/npnf104.iv.iv.xxi.html |author=[[Augustine_of_Hippo|Augustine of Hippo]] |title=Chapter 19 |work=On the Morals of the Catholic Church |accessdate=2007-03-15}}</ref><ref>Raymond, p. 78.</ref> Drunkenness, on the other hand, is considered a manifestation of [[gluttony|gluttony]], one of the [[seven_deadly_sins|seven deadly sins]] as compiled by [[Pope_Gregory_I|Gregory the Great]] in the 6th century.<ref>[[Pope_Gregory_I|Gregory the Great]]. ''[[Commentary_on_Job|Moralia in Job]]'', book 31, chapter 45.</ref>
