icles_of_Religion_(Methodist)|Articles of Religion]] (1784).<ref>[http://www.ccel.org/ccel/schaff/creeds3.v.vi.html#v.vi-p42 Article 18]</ref> In the [[Dordrecht_Confession_of_Faith|Dordrecht Confession of Faith]] (1632), even the radical [[Anabaptist|Anabaptist]]s, who sought to expunge every trace of Roman Catholicism and to rely only on the Bible, also assumed wine was to be used,<ref>[http://www.gameo.org/encyclopedia/contents/D674.html#X Article 10]</ref> and despite their reputation as killjoys,<ref>{{cite book|title=Puritans at Play |url=https://archive.org/details/puritansatplayle00dani |author=Bruce C. Daniels |isbn=0-312-16124-7 |year=1996 |publisher=Palgrave Macmillan |page=3ff}}</ref> the English [[Puritan|Puritan]]s were temperate partakers of "God's good gifts," including wine and ale.<ref>West, ''Drinking'', pp. 68ff.</ref>
