[[John_Wesley|John Wesley]] warned: "You see the wine when it sparkles in the cup, and are going to drink of it. I tell you there is poison in it! and, therefore, beg you to throw it away." <ref>{{cite book|first=John|last=Wesley|title=Sermons of John Wesley|chapter=Sermon 140, On Public Diversions|url=http://wesley.nnu.edu/john-wesley/the-sermons-of-john-wesley-1872-edition/sermon-140-on-public-diversions/|accessdate=2013-11-15}}</ref>

Wesley likewise deplored [[distilled_beverage|distilled beverage]]s such as [[brandy|brandy]] and [[whisky|whisky]] when they were used non-medicinally, and he said the many [[distillation|distillers]] who sold indiscriminately to anyone were nothing more than poisoners and murderers accursed by God.<ref>{{cite book |title=The Sermons of John Wesley |editor=Thomas Jackson (ed.)|year=1999 |author=John Wesley |chapter=On the Use of Money |chapterurl=http://wesley.nnu.edu/john_wesley/sermons/050.htm |accessdate=2008-05-20 |publisher=Wesley Center for Applied Theology at Northwest Nazarene University |origyear=1872}}</ref> In 1744, the directions the Wesleys gave to the Methodist band societies (small groups of Methodists intended to support living a Christian life) required them "to taste no spirituous [i.e., [[distilled_beverage|distilled]]] liquor ... unless prescribed by a physician."<ref>{{cite book |author=Methodist Episcopal Church |others=with explanatory notes by Thomas Coke and Francis Asbury |title=Doctrines and Discipline of the Methodist Episcopal Church |year=1798 |chapter=Directions given to the Band-Societies. December 25th, 1744. |edition=10th |chapterurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=zOoCAAAAQAAJ&pg=RA1-PA150 |page=150}}</ref> At the 1780 Methodist Conference in [[Baltimore|Baltimore]], the churchmen opposed distilled liquors and determined to "disown those who would not renounce the practice" of producing it.<ref name="Bangs">{{cite book |author=Nathan Bangs |title=A History of the Methodist Episcopal Church |volume=1 |year=1838 |publisher=T. Mason and G. Lane for the Methodist Episcopal Church |location=New York |url=http://books.google.com/?id=vSURAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA134 |page=134f}}</ref> In opposing liquors, the American Methodists anticipated the first wave of the temperance movement that would follow,<ref name="Bangs"/> and though they expanded their membership rule regarding alcohol to include other alcoholic beverages over the next century, they afterwards reverted to Wesley's—namely, to avoid "[d]runkenness, buying or selling spirituous [i.e., distilled] liquors, or drinking them, unless in cases of extreme necessity".<ref>{{cite book |author=Henry J. Fox and William B. Hoyt |chapter=Rule Respecting Intoxicating Liquors |title=Quadrennial Register of the Methodist Episcopal Church |year=1852 |publisher=Case, Tiffany & Co. |location=Connecticut |url=http://books.google.com/?id=YNeBt07_IaUC&pg=PA200 |page=200f}}</ref>

